## Session 36 Summary: Fresh Perspective

**7 experiments tested across 5 parallel agents + main thread, all CLOSED:**

| # | Experiment | Verdict | Key Finding |
|---|-----------|---------|-------------|
| 1 | Batch Möbius recursive halving | CLOSED | Trades depth for exponential breadth — 2^{π(√x)} total work unchanged |
| 2 | Automata digit DP | CLOSED | DFA minimal at primorial(B) states — e^{√x} for exact count |
| 3 | Adelic CRT mod q | CLOSED | 6th CRT variant fails — floor division not a ring homomorphism |
| 4 | Self-correcting explicit formula | CLOSED | Truncation bias is systematic O(N), not correctable by constraints |
| 5 | Ono partition criterion | CLOSED | O(n^{3/2}) best case — worse than Meissel-Lehmer |
| 6 | Convolution sieve via NTT | CLOSED | Additive (FFT) vs multiplicative (sieve) structural mismatch |
| 7 | Local-to-global reconstruction | CLOSED | **But found key quantitative insight** (see below) |

**Web research (2025-2026):** No progress toward polylog in the literature. Best new result: Aggarwal 2025, O(√n log⁴n) for p(n).

### KEY INSIGHT (quantified for first time):

**E(x) = pi(x) - Li(x) has only O(log x) bits of information.** At x = 10^100, the error needs ~160 bits but the polylog budget is ~110,000 bits. The barrier is **not information-theoretic** — it's purely computational: those O(log x) bits are encoded across ~x^{1/2} zeta zero contributions that massively cancel. Finding algebraic structure in this cancellation (like how geometric series collapse many oscillating terms) remains the only viable path.

**Total approaches tested: 655+ across 36 sessions.**

